{"id": "8f85ff88ecce4d99be2fff339335ff05", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 22:54:33", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Thought: The proposed topic addresses a critical and underexplored challenge at the intersection of interactive machine learning, robust optimization, and behavioral economics. By focusing on query-based search under bounded adversarial noise in the context of optimal price range estimation, it advances beyond classical noisy binary search models that assume random errors, instead accounting for structured, context-dependent human inconsistencies. The integration of adaptive error detection, learning-augmented priors with residual correction, and noise-aware scheduling introduces novel algorithmic mechanisms with strong theoretical and practical potential. Furthermore, the emphasis on behaviorally grounded evaluation—measuring cognitive load and perceived fairness—ensures real-world relevance in AI-driven economic interactions. This direction is timely, given the increasing deployment of personalized pricing and negotiation systems, and fills a key gap in sequential preference elicitation under unreliable feedback. The topic is sufficiently focused to guide concrete research milestones while being generalizable to domains like healthcare, e-commerce, and decision support, making it both innovative and impactful.\n\nTopic: ```json{\"Selected Topic\": \"Robust Query-Based Search under Bounded Adversarial Noise for Optimal Price Range Estimation\"}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "dce5ab2f2b524e6584e74d22f0909a33", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 22:54:37", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "The selected topic focuses on developing robust query-based search algorithms for optimal price range estimation under bounded adversarial noise, addressing limitations of classical models that assume random errors. It integrates adaptive noisy binary search, learning-augmented frameworks, and behaviorally informed evaluation to handle structured human inconsistencies in preference elicitation. The approach enables theoretically grounded, empirically testable advancements with broad applicability in personalized AI-driven systems like e-commerce and decision support, while capturing cognitive load and fairness in human-AI interaction. This direction is now locked in to enable forward progress on modeling, algorithm design, and validation.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
